# {{lb|en|grammar}} A [[noun]] that is [[morphologically]] related to a [[verb]] and similar to it in meaning; in English, it contrasts with gerund and deverbal noun. It is a pure noun with no verbal force, so it cannot take an object or an adverb (as a [[gerund]] can), however, it can be part of a possessive construction ''(the visiting of a friend)'' and it can take an adjective ''(fast driving)'' as other nouns can. On the other hand, it still refers to the abstract action or occurrence implied in the verb, as opposed to (e.g.) its result, as a [[deverbal noun]] does.

==== Usage notes ====
Traditional grammarians often used the term "verbal noun" as a synonym for gerund.
:* ''Brisk '''walking''' is good exercise.''

